Packages and Interfaces in Java


ğŸ’¡ 1. Packages in Java
âœ… Definition

A package in Java is a collection of related classes, interfaces, and sub-packages.
It helps organize code, avoid name conflicts, and control access.

You can think of a package like a folder in your file system.

ğŸ”¹ Types of Packages
Type	Description	Example
Built-in Packages	Provided by Java API	java.util, java.io, java.net
User-defined Packages	Created by the programmer	package mypack;
ğŸ”¹ Syntax for Creating a Package
package mypack; // must be the first statement

public class Message {
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Hello from mypack!");
    }
}


To compile and run:

javac -d . Message.java   // creates folder structure
java mypack.Message

ğŸ”¹ Importing Packages
Syntax	Use
import packageName.ClassName;	Import a single class
import packageName.*;	Import all classes from the package
import static packageName.ClassName.methodName;	Import static members only

Example:

import java.util.*; // imports all utility classes
import mypack.Message; // imports user-defined class

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Message obj = new Message();
        obj.display();
    }
}

ğŸ”’ 2. Access Protection (Access Modifiers)

Access modifiers control visibility of classes, methods, and variables across packages.

Modifier	Within Class	Same Package	Subclass (Other Package)	Other Packages
private	âœ…	âŒ	âŒ	âŒ
default (no modifier)	âœ…	âœ…	âŒ	âŒ
protected	âœ…	âœ…	âœ…	âŒ
public	âœ…	âœ…	âœ…	âœ…
ğŸ”¹ Example of Access Control
package school;

public class Student {
    public int rollNo = 1;
    private String name = "Riya";
    protected String course = "Java";
    int age = 20; // default
}

package test;
import school.Student;

public class AccessDemo extends Student {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        AccessDemo obj = new AccessDemo();
        System.out.println(obj.rollNo);    // accessible (public)
        System.out.println(obj.course);    // accessible (protected)
        // System.out.println(obj.name);   // not accessible (private)
        // System.out.println(obj.age);    // not accessible (default)
    }
}

âš™ï¸ 3. Interfaces in Java
âœ… Definition

An interface in Java is a fully abstract class that contains only abstract methods (and constants by default).

It is used to achieve abstraction and multiple inheritance.

ğŸ”¹ Syntax
interface InterfaceName {
    // by default: public, abstract, and final
    void method1();
    void method2();
}

ğŸ”¹ Implementing an Interface

A class uses the implements keyword to provide implementation for interface methods.

interface Animal {
    void sound();
}

class Dog implements Animal {
    public void sound() {  // must be public
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

public class InterfaceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a = new Dog();  // interface reference
        a.sound();
    }
}


Output:

Dog barks

ğŸ”¹ 4. Applying Multiple Interfaces

A class can implement multiple interfaces (unlike classes, which allow only single inheritance).

interface A {
    void methodA();
}

interface B {
    void methodB();
}

class C implements A, B {
    public void methodA() {
        System.out.println("Method A");
    }

    public void methodB() {
        System.out.println("Method B");
    }
}

public class MultipleInterfaces {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        C obj = new C();
        obj.methodA();
        obj.methodB();
    }
}


Output:

Method A
Method B

ğŸ”¹ 5. Extending Interfaces

Interfaces can also extend other interfaces (just like classes), allowing interface inheritance.

interface Vehicle {
    void start();
}

interface Car extends Vehicle {
    void accelerate();
}

class Honda implements Car {
    public void start() {
        System.out.println("Honda starting...");
    }

    public void accelerate() {
        System.out.println("Honda accelerating...");
    }
}

public class InterfaceInheritance {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Honda h = new Honda();
        h.start();
        h.accelerate();
    }
}


Output:

Honda starting...
Honda accelerating...

ğŸ’¡ 6. Default and Static Methods in Interface (Java 8+)

Interfaces can now include default and static methods with implementations.

interface Demo {
    default void greet() {
        System.out.println("Hello from default method!");
    }

    static void info() {
        System.out.println("Static method in interface");
    }
}

class DemoClass implements Demo { }

public class DefaultStaticDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        DemoClass d = new DemoClass();
        d.greet();          // calls default method
        Demo.info();        // calls static method
    }
}

ğŸ§¾ 7. Summary Table
Concept	Keyword	Example
Package	package	package mypack;
Import	import	import java.util.*;
Access Modifier	public, protected, private	public class A {}
Interface Definition	interface	interface A { void show(); }
Implementation	implements	class B implements A {}
Interface Inheritance	extends	interface B extends A {}
âœ… 8. Advantages
Concept	Benefit
Packages	Organizes classes, avoids name conflicts, provides access control.
Interfaces	Provides abstraction, supports multiple inheritance, enforces contract between class and interface.
